<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="9" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1804,2009]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1437,151,1256]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="9" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1804,1829]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
(Based on 
<bibRefCitation author="Bray, R. A." box="[403,538,1804,1829]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="683 - 685" refId="ref33018" refString="Bray, R. A. (2005 b) Family Megaperidae Manter, 1934. In: Jones, A., Bray, R. A. &amp; Gibson, D. I. (Eds.), Keys to the Trematoda. Vol. 2. CABI Publishing and the Natural History Museum, Wallingford, pp. 683 - 685." type="book chapter" year="2005">Bray 2005b</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Pulis, E. E. &amp; Curran, S. S. &amp; Andres, M. J. &amp; Overstreet, R. M." box="[551,738,1804,1829]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="269 - 274" refId="ref35336" refString="Pulis, E. E., Curran, S. S., Andres, M. J. &amp; Overstreet, R. M. (2014) Change in rank of Megaperidae (Trematoda) to Megaperinae within the Apocreadiidae and description of Haintestinum amplum n. g., n. sp. Parasitology International, 63, 269 - 274. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. parint. 2013.11.007" type="journal article" year="2014">
Pulis 
<emphasis box="[615,666,1804,1829]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">et al</emphasis>
. 2014
</bibRefCitation>
) Body small, rounded, oval or elongate. Tegument spinous at anterior extremity; posterior extent of spines variable. Eye-spot pigment present. Oral sucker subterminal, oval, globular or infundibuliform, larger than ventral sucker. Ventral sucker round, equatorial or pre-equatorial. Prepharynx present. Pharynx weakly muscular, cup-shaped, with lobed anterior margin. Esophagus present or absent. Intestinal bifurcation in mid-forebody. Caeca broad to narrow, with or without anterior extensions to oral sucker, open via ani at posterior extremity. Testes two, large, tandem or opposite, pre-ovarian or post-ovarian, in forebody or hindbody. Cirrus pouch absent. Seminal vesicle saccate to elongate, near ventral sucker. Pars prostatica globular, well-developed; prostatic cells present. Genital atrium short, muscular or shallow. Genital pore median, in posterior region of forebody. Ovary subspherical or lobed, at level of ventral sucker or anterior hindbody, median or submedian, pre- or post-testicular. Canalicular seminal receptacle and Mehlis’ gland present. Laurer’s canal present or absent. Vitellarium follicular; follicles lateral, in hindbody only or in both hindbody and forebody. Uterus short, extends posteriorly to level of ovary. Eggs few to many, medium to large, thin-shelled. Excretory vesicle I-shaped in adults, Y-shaped in cercariae; excretory pore terminal. Eggs unembryonated when laid, embryonate to produce miracidia which infect marine calyptraeid snails wherein polyembryony produces rediae that develop oculate cercariae that are shed out into open environment, encyst, and develop metacercariae infective to definitive host. Adults in intestine of marine teleosts (
<taxonomicName box="[780,994,476,501]" class="Actinopterygii" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tetraodontiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Tetraodontiformes</taxonomicName>
); NW Atlantic Ocean.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,626,511,536]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="type_taxon">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,1256]" box="[199,626,511,536]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,340,511,536]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<typeStatus box="[199,258,511,536]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Type</typeStatus>
genus.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Manter, 1934" authorityName="Manter" authorityYear="1934" box="[347,623,512,536]" class="Trematoda" family="Megaperidae" genus="Megapera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plagiorchiida" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[347,462,513,536]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Megapera</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Manter, H. W." box="[469,623,512,536]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="293" refId="ref34609" refString="Manter, H. W. (1934) Megapera, new name for the trematode genus Eurypera Manter, 1933. Transactions of the American Microscopical Society, 53, 293. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 3222107" type="journal article" year="1934">Manter, 1934</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,1256]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,548,573]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Remarks.</emphasis>
Members of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Manter" authorityYear="1934" box="[511,657,548,573]" class="Trematoda" family="Apocreadiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plagiorchiida" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Megaperinae">Megaperinae</taxonomicName>
are unique within the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Manter" authorityYear="1934" box="[915,1061,548,573]" class="Trematoda" family="Megaperidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plagiorchiida" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="family">Megaperidae</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1069,1172,548,573]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">n. comb.</emphasis>
in possessing a genital pore anterior to the ventral sucker, an oral sucker lacking a partial U-shaped sphincter encircling the aperture of the sucker, and caeca that open via ani. The main features used to distinguish the three recognized genera of megaperines include the morphology of the intestine (H-shaped 
<emphasis box="[868,891,657,680]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">vs</emphasis>
caeca posteriorly-directed only), the presence or absence of an esophagus, the presence or absence of radiating alternating muscular and cellular bands within the oral sucker, and whether or not the oral sucker is enclosed in a fold of the body wall (
<bibRefCitation author="Bray, R. A." box="[1093,1229,727,752]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="683 - 685" refId="ref33018" refString="Bray, R. A. (2005 b) Family Megaperidae Manter, 1934. In: Jones, A., Bray, R. A. &amp; Gibson, D. I. (Eds.), Keys to the Trematoda. Vol. 2. CABI Publishing and the Natural History Museum, Wallingford, pp. 683 - 685." type="book chapter" year="2005">Bray 2005b</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Cribb, T. H." box="[1240,1369,727,752]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="621 - 639" refId="ref33192" refString="Cribb, T. H. (2005) Family Apocreadiidae Skrjabin, 1942. In: Jones, A., Bray, R. A. &amp; Gibson, D. I. (Eds.), Keys to the Trematoda. Vol. 2. CABI Publishing and the Natural History Museum, Wallingford, pp. 621 - 639." type="book chapter" year="2005">Cribb 2005</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Pulis, E. E. &amp; Curran, S. S. &amp; Andres, M. J. &amp; Overstreet, R. M." pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="269 - 274" refId="ref35336" refString="Pulis, E. E., Curran, S. S., Andres, M. J. &amp; Overstreet, R. M. (2014) Change in rank of Megaperidae (Trematoda) to Megaperinae within the Apocreadiidae and description of Haintestinum amplum n. g., n. sp. Parasitology International, 63, 269 - 274. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. parint. 2013.11.007" type="journal article" year="2014">
Pulis 
<emphasis box="[151,200,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">et al</emphasis>
. 2014
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,1256]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
As detailed earlier, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Manter" authorityYear="1934" box="[428,543,801,824]" class="Trematoda" family="Megaperidae" genus="Megapera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plagiorchiida" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[428,543,801,824]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Megapera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Syn. 
<taxonomicName authority="Manter, 1933" authorityName="Manter" authorityYear="1933" box="[625,895,800,824]" class="Trematoda" family="Apocreadiidae" genus="Eurypera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plagiorchiida" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[625,731,801,824]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Eurypera</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Manter, H. W." box="[741,895,800,824]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="233 - 242" refId="ref34568" refString="Manter, H. W. (1933) A new family of trematodes from marine fishes. Transactions of the American Microscopical Society, 52, 233 - 242. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 3222258" type="journal article" year="1933">Manter, 1933</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis box="[906,945,801,824]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">nec</emphasis>
Pascoe, 1870) was established by 
<bibRefCitation author="Manter, H. W." pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="233 - 242" refId="ref34568" refString="Manter, H. W. (1933) A new family of trematodes from marine fishes. Transactions of the American Microscopical Society, 52, 233 - 242. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 3222258" type="journal article" year="1933">Manter (1933</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Manter, H. W." box="[232,292,836,860]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="293" refId="ref34609" refString="Manter, H. W. (1934) Megapera, new name for the trematode genus Eurypera Manter, 1933. Transactions of the American Microscopical Society, 53, 293. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 3222107" type="journal article" year="1934">1934</bibRefCitation>
), who described the 
<typeStatus box="[530,578,837,861]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">type</typeStatus>
species, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Manter, 1933) Manter, 1934" authorityName="Manter" authorityYear="1934" baseAuthorityName="Manter" baseAuthorityYear="1933" box="[684,1252,836,861]" class="Trematoda" family="Megaperidae" genus="Megapera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plagiorchiida" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="pseudura">
<emphasis box="[684,912,836,861]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Megapera pseudura</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Manter, H. W." box="[929,1083,836,860]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="233 - 242" refId="ref34568" refString="Manter, H. W. (1933) A new family of trematodes from marine fishes. Transactions of the American Microscopical Society, 52, 233 - 242. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 3222258" type="journal article" year="1933">Manter, 1933</bibRefCitation>
) 
<bibRefCitation author="Manter, H. W." box="[1100,1252,836,860]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="293" refId="ref34609" refString="Manter, H. W. (1934) Megapera, new name for the trematode genus Eurypera Manter, 1933. Transactions of the American Microscopical Society, 53, 293. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 3222107" type="journal article" year="1934">Manter, 1934</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(Syn. 
<taxonomicName authority="Manter, 1933" authorityName="Manter" authorityYear="1933" class="Trematoda" family="Apocreadiidae" genus="Eurypera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plagiorchiida" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="pseudura">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Eurypera pseudura</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Manter, H. W." box="[267,424,872,896]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="233 - 242" refId="ref34568" refString="Manter, H. W. (1933) A new family of trematodes from marine fishes. Transactions of the American Microscopical Society, 52, 233 - 242. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 3222258" type="journal article" year="1933">Manter, 1933</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
), from the intestine of the scrawled cowfish, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[967,1148,871,896]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Ostraciidae" genus="Lactophrys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tetraodontiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="quadricornis">
<emphasis box="[967,984,872,895]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1003,1148,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">quadricornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from off Dry 
<collectingCountry box="[1331,1432,872,896]" name="Haiti" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Tortugas</collectingCountry>
, Florida. In that same publication, 
<bibRefCitation author="Manter, H. W." box="[529,691,908,932]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="233 - 242" refId="ref34568" refString="Manter, H. W. (1933) A new family of trematodes from marine fishes. Transactions of the American Microscopical Society, 52, 233 - 242. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 3222258" type="journal article" year="1933">Manter (1933)</bibRefCitation>
erected 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Manter" authorityYear="1933" box="[786,973,908,933]" class="Trematoda" family="Megaperidae" genus="Thysanopharynx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plagiorchiida" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[786,973,908,933]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Thysanopharynx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with the description of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Manter" authorityYear="1933" box="[1238,1375,908,933]" class="Trematoda" family="Megaperidae" genus="Thysanopharynx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plagiorchiida" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="elongatus">
<emphasis box="[1238,1375,908,933]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">T. elongatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the same host species and locality. 
<bibRefCitation author="Pulis, E. E. &amp; Curran, S. S. &amp; Andres, M. J. &amp; Overstreet, R. M." box="[538,737,943,968]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="269 - 274" refId="ref35336" refString="Pulis, E. E., Curran, S. S., Andres, M. J. &amp; Overstreet, R. M. (2014) Change in rank of Megaperidae (Trematoda) to Megaperinae within the Apocreadiidae and description of Haintestinum amplum n. g., n. sp. Parasitology International, 63, 269 - 274. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. parint. 2013.11.007" type="journal article" year="2014">
Pulis 
<emphasis box="[600,648,943,968]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">et al</emphasis>
. (2014)
</bibRefCitation>
erected 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pulis, Curran, Andres &amp; Overstreet" authorityYear="2014" box="[830,981,945,968]" class="Trematoda" family="Apocreadiidae" genus="Haintestinum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plagiorchiida" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[830,981,945,968]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Haintestinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and described 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pulis, Curran, Andres &amp; Overstreet" authorityYear="2014" box="[1148,1272,943,968]" class="Trematoda" family="Apocreadiidae" genus="Haintestinum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plagiorchiida" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="amplum">
<emphasis box="[1148,1168,945,968]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1182,1272,943,968]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">amplum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
obtained from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[151,329,980,1005]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Ostraciidae" genus="Lactophrys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tetraodontiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="quadricornis">
<emphasis box="[151,168,980,1003]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[184,329,980,1005]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">quadricornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
off Florida in the eastern Gulf of Mexico. The single species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pulis, Curran, Andres &amp; Overstreet" authorityYear="2014" box="[1084,1235,981,1004]" class="Trematoda" family="Apocreadiidae" genus="Haintestinum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plagiorchiida" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1084,1235,981,1004]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Haintestinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
known to date is unique in that it possesses an intestine composed of paired caeca directed anteriorly and posteriorly (H-shaped) and has an esophagus; members of the other two genera of megaperines have neither of these features. Members of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Manter" authorityYear="1934" box="[151,266,1089,1112]" class="Trematoda" family="Megaperidae" genus="Megapera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plagiorchiida" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,266,1089,1112]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Megapera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Manter" authorityYear="1933" box="[322,509,1087,1112]" class="Trematoda" family="Megaperidae" genus="Thysanopharynx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plagiorchiida" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[322,509,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Thysanopharynx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be differentiated by the former having an oral sucker that is much larger than the ventral sucker with radiating alternating muscle and cellular bands and an oral sucker not enclosed in a fold of the body wall; whereas, species of the latter genus have an oral sucker only slightly larger than the ventral sucker, lack distinct radiating muscle bands and the oral sucker is almost wholly enclosed in a fold of the body wall (
<bibRefCitation author="Bray, R. A." pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="683 - 685" refId="ref33018" refString="Bray, R. A. (2005 b) Family Megaperidae Manter, 1934. In: Jones, A., Bray, R. A. &amp; Gibson, D. I. (Eds.), Keys to the Trematoda. Vol. 2. CABI Publishing and the Natural History Museum, Wallingford, pp. 683 - 685." type="book chapter" year="2005">Bray 2005b</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Pulis, E. E. &amp; Curran, S. S. &amp; Andres, M. J. &amp; Overstreet, R. M." box="[235,421,1231,1256]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="269 - 274" refId="ref35336" refString="Pulis, E. E., Curran, S. S., Andres, M. J. &amp; Overstreet, R. M. (2014) Change in rank of Megaperidae (Trematoda) to Megaperinae within the Apocreadiidae and description of Haintestinum amplum n. g., n. sp. Parasitology International, 63, 269 - 274. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. parint. 2013.11.007" type="journal article" year="2014">
Pulis 
<emphasis box="[298,347,1231,1256]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">et al</emphasis>
. 2014
</bibRefCitation>
). Given this information, we consider the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Manter" authorityYear="1934" box="[889,1035,1231,1256]" class="Trematoda" family="Apocreadiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plagiorchiida" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Megaperinae">Megaperinae</taxonomicName>
to be a distinct, well-defined taxon.
</paragraph>
